{"cursor":"8759","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\nA 'perimeter' is a path that surrounds an area. The word comes from the Greek\nperi (around) and meter (measure). The term may be used either for the path or\nits length - it can be thought of as the length of the outline of a shape. The\nperimeter of a circular area is called its circumference.\n\nCalculating the perimeter has considerable practical applications. The perimeter\ncan be used to calculate the length of fence required to surround a yard or\ngarden. The perimeter of a wheel (its circumference) describes how far it will\nroll in one revolution. Similarly, the amount of string wound around a spool is\nrelated to the spool's perimeter.\n","linknr":284,"url":"Perimeter","recorded":1362689182,"links":81,"instances":["geometry","mathematics","geometry","geometry","geometry","geometry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Elementary geometry","Length"],"headings":["Formulae","Polygons","Circumference of a circle","Perception of perimeter","Isoperimetry","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Perimiters.svg/250px-Perimiters.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/f/0/4f0f2463c6cce308b00799ddfcb3d923.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/b/4/4b43b0aee35624cd95b910189b3dc231.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/e/8/7e8db2b4cd002e46f7bb8bfe4f24217c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/c/c/0cc175b9c0f1b6a831c399e269772661.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/2/e/92eb5ffee6ae2fec3ad71c777531578f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/a/8/4a8a08f09d37b73795649038408b5f33.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/1/e/21e1dcd96ade2d871bb13381006a5f67.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/c/c/0cc175b9c0f1b6a831c399e269772661.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/0/c/20c38c58b6a37e1ee023a3b6bc769a75.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/5/1/2510c39011c5be704182423e3a695e91.png","//upload.